1. Did you try `member` instead?  I'm looking [here](http://www.sphinx-doc.org/en/stable/domains.html#directive-cpp:var), but I'm pretty sure that won't fix this.
2. The underlying problem here is that the `var` doesn't have the template, the class does.  The impact is that in the doxygen xml output, `messageHandlers` will have the `templateparamlist`, not the specific variable you are documenting.

So the fix you probably don't want to use is to explicitly specialize the `messageHandlers` class for `Go` and `Stop`, adding documentation to each specialization

```
class Stop;
class Go;

//! stores a handler for each message type.
template<typename T>
struct messageHandlers {
    typedef std::function<void (const T&)> type;
    static type handler;
};

template <>
struct messageHandlers<Stop> {
    typedef std::function<void (const Stop&)> type;
    static type handler;
};
```

Definitely defeats the purpose... but then you can do `.. doxygenclass:: messageHandlers< Stop >`.  This will produce warnings, but I'm here trying to fix those ;)

Alternatively, just add documentation to `messageHandlers` and explicitly state that specializations for `Stop` and `Go` exist?

