@joeherm Yes, I did find a solution. I needed to configure the custom models like this instead:

```python
OAUTH2_PROVIDER = {
    'SCOPES': {
        'read': 'Read scope',
        'write': 'Write scope',
    }
}
OAUTH2_PROVIDER_APPLICATION_MODEL = 'fm_django_auth.Oauth2Application'
OAUTH2_PROVIDER_ACCESS_TOKEN_MODEL = 'fm_django_auth.Oauth2AccessToken'
OAUTH2_PROVIDER_REFRESH_TOKEN_MODEL = 'fm_django_auth.Oauth2RefreshToken'
OAUTH2_PROVIDER_GRANT_MODEL = 'fm_django_auth.Oauth2Grant'
```

The difference between my initial configuration and this "new" configuration is that the old one essentially overrides properties on an already-instantiated settings object (hence the Model error, since Django has already instantiated the oAuth lib's own models); the new approach causes the oAuth lib to instantiate my custom models *instead of its own models* during the settings object's instantiation.

